  "prompt": "What are some good science documentaries, other than Stephen Hawking's Grand Design?",
  "response": "There are many excellent science documentaries that explore a variety of topics in an engaging and enlightening way. Here are some recommendations:\n\n1. **Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey** - Hosted by Neil deGrasse Tyson, this series is a sequel to Carl Sagan's \"Cosmos: A Personal Journey\" and explores the universe, scientific concepts, and the history of science.\n\n2. **Our Planet** - Narrated by David Attenborough, this visually stunning series focuses on the natural world and the impact of climate change on various ecosystems.\n\n3. **The Theory of Everything** - This biographical film about Stephen Hawking also contains elements of science documentation, exploring his life, work, and the complexities of black holes and the universe.\n\n4. **The Universe** - A documentary series that delves into the cosmos, covering various aspects of astronomy and space exploration.\n\n5. **What Is a Woman?** - A thought-provoking exploration of gender identity and the science of sex and gender, this documentary challenges preconceptions and encourages discussion.\n\n6. **Particle Fever** - This documentary follows the scientists working on the Large Hadron Collider during the discovery of the Higgs boson, showcasing the excitement and challenges of cutting-edge research.\n\n7. **Chasing Ice** - Focusing on climate change, this documentary chronicles photographer James Balog's mission to capture evidence of climate change through time-lapse photography of glaciers.\n\n8. **My Octopus Teacher** - This unique documentary follows filmmaker Craig Foster as he forges a bond with an octopus in a South African kelp forest, revealing insights into marine life and the connections within nature.\n\n9. **The Social Dilemma** - While it focuses on social media, this documentary explains the psychological and sociological impacts of technology, blending psychology with a science-based approach to modern issues.\n\n10. **Before the Flood** - Produced by National Geographic, this documentary features Leonardo DiCaprio exploring the effects of climate change and highlighting potential solutions.\n\nThese documentaries vary in topics but all aim to inspire curiosity and deepen understanding of the world through scientific exploration.",
